gdel 1951 : in this lecture\, kurt gdel uses the incompleteness theorem to arrive at the following disjunction: (a) the human mind is not a consistent finite machine\, or (b) there exist diophantine equations for which it cannot decide whether solutions exist. gdel finds (b) implausible\, and thus seems to have believed the human mind was not equivalent to a finite machine\, i.e.\, its power exceeded that of any finite machine. he recognized that this was only a conjecture\, since one could never disprove (b). yet he considered the disjunctive conclusion to be a certain fact.
